The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   Business Briefs
                              
	 New Delhi, June 18: About 92 per cent of the income- tax refund claims for 2007-08 fiscal will be settled without the taxpayers needing to produce TDS certificates as the government has relaxed the criteria in this regard. According to the relaxed criteria, for tax assessee whose tax is deducted up to Rs 5 lakh and who has filed refund claims of up to Rs 25,000, TDS certificates such as form-16 or challans will not be verified.                            
	 New Delhi, June 18: The growth of core industries skidded to 3.6 per cent in the first month of the current fiscal as electricity generation and petroleum output rose at a dismal pace.                             
	 Mumbai, June 18: Shekhar Datta has resigned as the chairman of the Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE). Jamshyd Godrej, a director on the BSE board, has also put in his papers. Though the reasons for their resignations could not be obtained, the speculation is that Datta complained of interference from brokers.                             
	 New Delhi, June 18: Indian Oil Corporation, ONGC and GAIL (India) have expressed interest in buying out Asian Development Banks (ADB) 5.2 per cent stake in Petronet LNG following ADBs offer to exit the countrys largest liquefied natural gas importing company.                             
	 Mumbai, June 18: Union Bank of India (UBI) plans to raise $ 2 billion (about Rs 8,000 crore) through medium term debt from international market to prop up its overseas expansion.                             
	 New Delhi, June 18: MTNL has received an international long-distance licence, a development which could signal a further lowering of ISD rates.                             
	 Mumbai, June 18: Religare Enterprises today said there were no concrete proposals to foray into the banking sector even as the company keeps on assessing various options to grow.                                                                                                                          
